📌 Event Bubbling in JavaScript
📖 What is Event Bubbling?

Event Bubbling is a mechanism in JavaScript where an event starts from the target element (the element that triggered the event) and then propagates upward through its parent elements in the DOM tree.

In simple words:

When you click a child element, the event also triggers on its parent, then grandparent, and so on.

🌳 How It Works (Conceptual Flow)

If we have this structure:

<div id="parent">
  <button id="child">Click Me</button>
</div>

When the button is clicked:

Event triggers on <button>

Then moves to <div>

Then to <body>

Then to <html>

Finally to document

This upward movement is called Event Bubbling.

🧠 Why It Happens?

Because the DOM is structured like a tree, and events naturally propagate through this tree.

Event flow has 3 phases:

Capturing Phase (top → target)

Target Phase

Bubbling Phase (target → top) ✅

By default, JavaScript handles events in the bubbling phase.

🛑 How to Stop Event Bubbling

You can stop bubbling using:

event.stopPropagation();

This prevents the event from moving to parent elements.

🚀 Why Event Bubbling is Useful?

Enables Event Delegation

Improves performance (attach one listener to parent instead of many children)

Makes dynamic elements easier to manage

📌 Example
document.getElementById("parent").addEventListener("click", function() {
  console.log("Parent clicked");
});

document.getElementById("child").addEventListener("click", function(event) {
  console.log("Child clicked");
});

Clicking the button will log:

Child clicked
Parent clicked

Because of Event Bubbling.